BRUSSELS, September 28 (Reuters) - After Italy flouted the EU's demands and surprised the market with a large-scale budget deficit plan, the EU took a non-confrontational stance against Italy on Friday, but if Italy insists on too bold goals, the EU may adopt a more radical stance.
Italy's suspected European government aims to run a budget deficit equivalent to 2.4% of gross domestic product (GDP) over the next three years, indicating that there is no debt reduction in the face of deficit reduction requirements.
"We have no interest in the crisis between the Executive Committee and Italy," said Moskevisi, the EU's executive committee on economic affairs, on Friday. "Since the EU's proposals and sanctions may have little impact on Italy, he took a cautious response.
EU officials and diplomats still hope that market forces will persuade Italy to adjust its budget plan before Italy is officially submitted to the EU Executive Committee in mid-October.
After the government announced its plan, the euro fell to its lowest level in nearly two weeks on Friday, while Italian bond yields hit their highest level in three weeks.
If the deficit target remains unchanged before the October deadline, the EU Executive Committee may veto Italy's draft budget, which is something that the Executive Committee has never done to any country.
Dong Brovsky, vice chairman of the EU Executive Committee, said at a meeting in the Latvian capital Riga on Friday that Italy's current fiscal plan "seems to be inconsistent with the stability and growth pact," referring to the EU's fiscal regulations.
But he did not say how this would trigger the EU's response.
