According to the subsidiary arrangement of the trade agreement announced on Monday, the new US-Mexico-Canada trade agreement will retain US President Trump's ability to implement the threat of a 25% tariff on imported cars, while basically exempting passenger cars, pickups and auto parts imported from Canada and Mexico from paying tariffs.
If Trump imposes a so-called "232 chapter" tariff on cars for national security reasons, then Mexico and Canada will have a quota of 2.6 million passenger cars exported to the United States each year.
According to the subsidiary arrangement, the pickup trucks produced in the two countries will be completely exempted from tariffs.
If Trump imposes auto tariffs, Mexico will receive an annual tax exemption quota of $108 billion for auto parts, and Canada will receive a quota of $32.4 billion.
Both quotas are much higher than the existing production levels of the two countries, providing room for growth for exports from the two countries.
WASHINGTON / MEXICO, September 28 (Reuters) - Mexico said on Friday that after several days of debate, US President Trump's government and Canada are making practical efforts to resolve trade policy differences, making the outside world hope that the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) is expected to maintain the tripartite agreement.
Although there is a lack of details, the above obvious progress is enough to prompt the Mexican and US governments to suddenly stop publishing the text of the two-party trade agreement and give Canada more time to join the agreement.
Mexican President-elect Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador told reporters in Mexico that the US government has made new counter-proposals to the Canadian government and said that he will continue to promote the participation of all three countries in NAFTA.
Mexico's economy minister, Ildefonso Guajardo, said that the time to submit the text of the US-Mexico trade agreement to Mexico and the US legislation was postponed because the Canadian and US governments "very seriously" tried to reach an agreement.
"In the next 48 hours, we will know whether we have reached a text of the tripartite agreement or have to publish the text of the two-party agreement," Guajardo said.
Guajardo said that his US and Canadian counterparts "specifically requested" to delay the release of the text.
A spokesman for the US Trade Representative's Office (USTR) did not comment on the text of the US-Mexico trade agreement and the US-Canada consultation.
Officials from the Canadian Prime Minister's Office and the Foreign Minister's Office did not respond to requests for comment on the counter-proposal.
According to foreign media reports, in a conservation center on the outskirts of Pretoria, the South African capital, two lions play together, and it is difficult to see any abnormalities, but they are unique.
The University of Pretoria announced: "This is the first young lion born by artificial insemination - the first pair in the world."
Scientists in the school are working hard to study the reproductive system of female African lions.
Gans Winter, director of the Institute of Mammal Research at the University of Pretoria, said that the two cubs born on August 25 are a male and female, quite healthy and normal.
After 18 months of intensive testing, his team finally reached this breakthrough.
"We collected sperm from a healthy lion," Ganswint said in a media interview.
Next, the researchers artificially inseminated the female lion when the hormone content in the body reached the appropriate level.
"Luckily, it turned out to be successful," Mr Ganswint said.
He said that the researchers "made several attempts, but unexpectedly, they did not spend much effort."
He said that the above research breakthroughs can be verified repeatedly, and scientists hope to use this technology to save endangered large cats.
The International Union for Conservation of Nature pointed out that lions have become extinct in 26 countries in Africa, and the total number of surviving wild lions has dropped by 43% in the past 20 years, leaving only about 20,000.
The African lion is listed as a vulnerable animal by this organization.
"If we don't do something for this animal, they will face extinction," Ganswint said.
He said that this new technology does not require the lion to be raised, but only the sperm is injected into the pregnant lioness, just like the North American and European practices for captive elephants.
South Korea's exports fell by the most in more than two years in September, but analysts attributed the decline to fewer working days and said that despite the rising trade tensions between China and the United States, global demand for Korean goods is still strong.
Indeed, South Korea's average daily exports increased last month.
In addition, the initial data released earlier showed double-digit growth in exports in the first weeks of September before the long holiday.
South Korea's exports fell year-on-year in September, the largest decline since July 2016, and the decline was greater than the 5.7% decline estimated by 11 analysts surveyed by Reuters.
The initial value released on Monday showed that exports in September were 50.6 billion US dollars, down from 51.2 billion US dollars in August.
Although the growing US-China trade dispute may cause other export-dependent Chinese neighbors to suffer, South Korea's exports to China grew by 7.8% in September, expanding for the 23rd consecutive month.
South Korea's exports to the United States fell by 11.8%, due to the decline in oil product sales.
Overseas sales of Korean memory chips and petroleum products increased by 28.3% and 13.5% respectively, although the market is worried that the so-called "super cycle" of chips may have peaked.
"However, the impact of trade conflicts will be difficult to avoid, because South Korea's exports depend to a considerable extent on the US and Chinese markets."
Imports fell 2.1% to 40.8 billion US dollars, which is not as good as the growth of 3.1% in the Reuters survey.
The initial trade surplus in September was $9.7 billion, up from $6.9 billion in August.
The Ministry of Industry said that thanks to the United States and EU countries, global manufacturing will remain prosperous, which is a favorable factor for South Korean exports.
The statement pointed out that "the increase in export prices caused by rising oil prices will also be beneficial to exports in the second half of this year."
"However, the continuation of the trade conflict between the United States and China, coupled with the increase in market volatility after the US interest rate hike, is a negative pressure on exports."
Exports per working day increased to $2.6 billion in September and $2.1 billion in August.
South Korea's Mid-Autumn Festival falls on September 24-26, so there are only 19.5 working days in September, four days less than the same period last year.
South Korea's exports from January to September increased by 4.7% compared with the same period last year.
According to the Nikkei / Markit Purchasing Managers Index, South Korean manufacturing activity rebounded in September, but was supported by domestic orders, because orders from China and Japan fell, which may cast another export outlook.
