Influenza vaccination services provided by health centres and health posts during the National Day holiday
The Health Bureau has ordered 150,000 doses of 2018-2019 four-price influenza vaccine this year. At this stage, priority is given to high-risk people to get free vaccination. In order to facilitate residents to get influenza vaccine during holidays, health centers and health stations under the Health Bureau provide vaccination services from 9 am to 1 noon during the National Day holiday (October 1 and 2).
In addition to the above convenience measures, the health centers and health stations under the Health Bureau have extended the flu vaccination service from Monday to Friday to 8 pm. As of 4 pm on September 30, 4,158 people have been vaccinated, compared with 3,714 in the same period last year.
The free vaccination targets include the following Macao residents: 6 months to 18 years of age, 50 years of age and above, pregnant women, all chronic patients, including obese people (that is, those with a body mass index BMI of 30 or more), as well as staff in institutions, nurseries, kindergartens, primary and secondary schools, all health workers, and Macao residents working in gaming casinos.
At the same time, the Health Bureau considers it necessary to vaccinate other personnel, including the public sector. The Health Bureau will take the initiative to contact the relevant organizations to obtain the list and arrange vaccination by the health center.
In order to facilitate vaccinators and reduce the waiting time for vaccination, the Health Bureau will send medical staff to primary schools, primary schools, kindergartens and nurseries in Hong Kong from October to December this year to conduct group vaccination for children, small and medium-sized students, teachers and employees. In addition, the Health Bureau will also arrange personnel to conduct group vaccination in elderly and disabled homes, public sector or other institutions with large numbers.
Students and young children who fail to participate in the group vaccination can take the Macao Resident Identity Card, the Health Bureau User Card, the Influenza Vaccination Card (if any), the student ID card, the employee ID card or the professional certificate to the Yan Long General Hospital vaccination station or the health center from December 3, 2018.
The Health Bureau reminds residents that between September 2017 and August 2018, people who have received the 2017-2018 influenza vaccine will still need to receive a new season of influenza vaccine from September 2018, because the influenza antigen contained in the 2018-2019 Northern Hemisphere influenza vaccine has been updated, which is aimed at the seasonal influenza in the Northern Hemisphere 2018-2019 winter and 2019 summer.
The peak period of influenza in Macao generally occurs from January to March of each year, which is later than that in temperate areas (such as northern China and Japan). The Health Bureau calls on the elderly, children, pregnant women, obese people and chronic patients who are more prone to complications after contracting influenza. High-risk people and those who are often exposed to high-risk people should be vaccinated as soon as possible.
