Reuters Hong Kong November 5th - Hong Kong property prices fell for two consecutive months after the peak. Chen Delin, president of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority, said on Monday that it is time to observe whether the property market has entered a downward cycle. If confirmed, it can be considered to relax the tightening policy of counter-cyclical measures in due course.
Chen Delin also pointed out that if the property price is adjusted back, the first people who will be affected will be those who buy their homes at the peak of the property market. However, it is expected that there will be a sharp drop in property prices during the Asian financial turmoil in 1997, and the public's chances of selling the property are much lower.
When Chen Delin led a number of senior HKMA officials to attend the Legislative Council briefing, he said that if it is confirmed that the property market has entered a downward cycle, it can relax measures in due course.
"But at present, only a few weeks of data have been seen. Relaxation is still said. It still takes more time to see whether the property market has entered a downward cycle."
Since October 2009, the HKMA has launched eight rounds of counter-cyclical measures to significantly tighten the mortgage of various types of properties, including reducing the number of mortgages and requiring mortgage applicants to pass rigorous stress tests to enhance bank risk management and earthquake resistance.
As Hong Kong officially entered the interest rate hike cycle, the Hong Kong private residential property price index peaked for two consecutive months from August to September, and the monthly decline in September expanded to 1.44%.
However, the cumulative increase in the first three quarters of this year still reached 10.2%.
According to the HKMA, the financial situation of households measuring the seismic capacity of Hong Kong to face financial risks is still healthy. In the second quarter of this year, the proportion of households without mortgages in Hong Kong reached 66%, which is higher than the average of 60% in 2009-11. The average number of mortgages approved and the ratio of contributions to income for newly approved mortgages were 47% and 34% respectively, which was significantly improved from 64% and 41% respectively in 2009-11.
However, Chen Delin said that the high seismic capacity does not mean that the residents will not be damaged by the economic downturn, because the property valuation will fall, and those who buy houses at the peak will bear the brunt.
Although the HKMA has tightened banks' lending to mortgage lenders, home buyers can also obtain high mortgage loans through mortgage insurance or mortgage loans provided by developers.
Mr Chan said that at present, together with the mortgage loans provided to developers, the number of borrowers can reach 85-90%. If the property price falls by 10%, there will be negative assets (that is, the market value of the property will fall below the level of the total amount of outstanding mortgage loans).
However, Ruan Guoheng, vice president of the HKMA, pointed out that the authorities estimate that the total amount of mortgages provided by developers is only 2-2.5% of the total amount of bank mortgages, and the proportion is still low.
At the peak of negative assets in Hong Kong in 2003, the number of negative assets exceeded 100,000, accounting for 22% of the supply.
As of the third quarter of this year, Hong Kong recorded zero negative assets for seven consecutive quarters.
