BEIJING, September 30 (Reuters) - China's central bank announced the net short-term outflow of foreign currency assets on Sunday. As of the end of August this year, the short position of the central bank's foreign currency against local currency forward contracts and futures contracts was zero for 12 consecutive months, and there was still no long position in the month.
The central bank's previous data showed that as of the end of August last year, the central bank held a short position of foreign currency against local currency forward contracts and futures contracts of 6.044 billion US dollars, which was the fourth consecutive month; the short position in SDR (special drawing rights) was 4.276 billion SDR.
Since then, the central bank's foreign exchange forward short position has been zero.
The central bank first released the data at the end of March 2016; the data showed that at the end of February 2016, the central bank's foreign currency position against local currency forward contracts and futures contracts was 2.438 billion US dollars, and the short position was 28.9 billion US dollars.
The September data released at the end of October of the same year showed a net short increase of 16.401 billion US dollars to 45.301 billion US dollars for the first time.
The central bank has previously said that the forward and futures short positions of foreign currencies against local currencies mainly reflect the foreign exchange forward operations carried out by the central bank with commercial banks to meet the hedging needs of corporate foreign currency liabilities. It will continue to provide long-term safe-haven products according to the principle of real demand. The impact of the central bank's long-term operation on the future foreign exchange reserve scale is small.
